pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR completes Phase 2.5 of the SumUp tap-to-pay integration, addressing all issues identified in #530. The implementation includes per-restaurant payment provider configuration, improved error handling, and a complete merchant onboarding flow.

## What Changed

### ðŸ” **Authentication & Configuration**
- Fixed authentication timing issue where SumUp config was fetched before user login
- Added `fetchConfigurationAfterAuth()` method to load config after successful authentication
- Config now gracefully handles missing auth tokens and defers initialization

### ðŸ’¾ **Per-Restaurant Payment Provider Storage**
- Created `restaurant_payment_providers` table with encrypted credential storage
- Implemented secure encryption module using Fernet symmetric encryption
- Each restaurant can now have their own SumUp merchant account

### ðŸŽ¨ **Merchant Onboarding UI**
- Built comprehensive onboarding screen for SumUp merchant account connection
- Real-time merchant code validation
- Support for multiple currencies (GBP, EUR, USD)
- Direct link to SumUp signup for new merchants

### ðŸ›¡ï¸ **Error Handling & User Feedback**
- Created `SumUpErrorHandler` with 15+ specific error codes
- User-friendly error messages with recovery actions
- Automatic retry suggestions for recoverable errors
- Clear guidance for configuration issues

### ðŸ”§ **Backend API Implementation**
- Complete SumUp API endpoints (`/sumup/initialize`, `/sumup/onboard`, `/sumup/status`)
- Pydantic schemas for type-safe API operations
- Support for merchant code validation
- Secure credential storage and retrieval

### ðŸ“± **iOS Native Module**
- Fixed compilation warnings in TapToPaySessionManager
- Verified Info.plist has all required permissions
- SDK initialization properly configured in AppDelegate

## Why

The previous implementation had critical issues:
1. **Authentication timing** - App crashed when fetching config before login
2. **Single merchant limitation** - All restaurants shared the same SumUp account
3. **Poor error handling** - Users got cryptic error messages
4. **No onboarding flow** - Restaurant owners couldn't connect their accounts

## Testing

### Manual Testing Checklist
- [ ] App starts without crashes when not logged in
- [ ] SumUp config loads after successful authentication
- [ ] Merchant onboarding flow completes successfully
- [ ] Credentials are properly encrypted in database
- [ ] Error messages are user-friendly and actionable
- [ ] Tap-to-pay works on physical iPhone with NFC
- [ ] Multiple restaurants can have different SumUp accounts

### Test Scenarios
1. **New Restaurant Setup**
   - Sign up for restaurant account
   - Navigate to Settings > Payment Providers
   - Complete SumUp onboarding
   - Process test payment

2. **Error Recovery**
   - Try payment without configuration
   - Verify error message guides to settings
   - Complete configuration and retry

3. **Multi-Tenant Isolation**
   - Configure SumUp for Restaurant A
   - Switch to Restaurant B
   - Verify different configuration

## Database Migration

Run the migration to create the new table:
```bash
alembic upgrade head
```

## Environment Variables

Ensure these are set in DigitalOcean:
- `SUMUP_AFFILIATE_KEY` - Your SumUp affiliate key
- `FYNLO_ENCRYPTION_KEY` - Key for encrypting credentials

## Screenshots

<details>
<summary>Merchant Onboarding Screen</summary>

- Clean UI for entering SumUp credentials
- Real-time validation feedback
- Security notice for user confidence
</details>

<details>
<summary>Error Handling Examples</summary>

- User-friendly error messages
- Clear recovery actions
- Retry options for transient failures
</details>

## Related Issues

Fixes #530 - Fix SumUp tap-to-pay integration for iOS (Phase 2.5)

## Deployment Notes

1. Deploy backend first (includes database migration)
2. Ensure environment variables are configured
3. Deploy iOS app with updated bundle
4. Test with real SumUp account and physical device

## Security Considerations

- All merchant credentials are encrypted at rest
- API keys never exposed in client code
- Per-restaurant isolation ensures data security
- Audit trail for credential changes
